- The Shovel Method adds items onto the end of an array using the code "<<". An example: 
  array_name = ["element_one", "element_two"]
  array_name << "element_three"
  p array_name
- The ".push" method, similar to the shovel method, will add an element to the end of an array. An example:
  array_name = ["element_one", "element_two"]
  array_name.push("element_three")
  p array_name
- The ".unshift" method will add an element to the beginning of an array. An example: 
  array_name = ["element_one", "element_two"]
  array_name.unshift("element_three")
  p array_name
- The ".pop" method will remove the last item from the end of the array. An example:
  array_name = ["element_one", "element_two"]
  array_name.pop
  p array_name
- The ".shift" method will remove the first item from the beginning of an array. An example:
  array_name = ["element_one", "element_two"]
  array_name.shift
  p array_name
- If you want to retrieve the index number for an element, we will use the ".index" method. An example:
  array_name = ["element_one", "element_two"]
  array_name.index("element_two")
- If you want to update or change an element within the array, we will have to determine the index. An example:
  picnic_ingrediants = ["Meat", "Bread", "Ball", "Vegetable"]
  picnic_ingrediants[2] = "Drink"
  p picnic_ingrediants 
